00:16:52.280 --> 00:16:55.640
 

00:16:55.640 --> 00:16:59.550
A prosaic but influential case was
decided by the Court of Appeals

00:16:59.550 --> 00:17:02.450
for the Ninth Circuit in 1996.

00:17:02.450 --> 00:17:05.839
The defendant, Cherry
Auction, was the operator

00:17:05.839 --> 00:17:10.190
of this flea market, located
in Fresno, California.

00:17:10.190 --> 00:17:13.579
A flea market, otherwise
known as a swap meet,

00:17:13.579 --> 00:17:16.790
is a marketplace where a large
number of independent vendors

00:17:16.790 --> 00:17:22.390
sell merchandise, typically
inexpensive or used merchandise,

00:17:22.390 --> 00:17:25.480
to customers who come
hunting for bargains.

00:17:25.480 --> 00:17:28.850
In this instance, the
vendors, as is typical,

00:17:28.850 --> 00:17:33.220
paid modest rental
fees to Cherry Auction.

00:17:33.220 --> 00:17:36.740
Cherry Auction provided
those vendors booth space,

00:17:36.740 --> 00:17:42.400
operated the parking facilities,
and advertised the marketplace.

00:17:42.400 --> 00:17:44.700
In addition to collect
the fees for the vendors,

00:17:44.700 --> 00:17:49.030
Cherry Auction collected entrance
fees from the customer's.

00:17:49.030 --> 00:17:51.570
Finally, Cherry Auction
reserved the right

00:17:51.570 --> 00:17:56.060
to exclude any vendor for any reason.

00:17:56.060 --> 00:17:59.710
The plaintiff, Fonovisa,
Incorporated, Owns?

00:17:59.710 --> 00:18:03.800
The copyrights in a large number
of Latino sound recordings.

00:18:03.800 --> 00:18:06.280
Fonovisa complained several
times at Cherry Auction

00:18:06.280 --> 00:18:08.030
that sum of the vendors
in the flea market

00:18:08.030 --> 00:18:14.540
were selling pirated copies of
Fonovisa's recordings to no available.

00:18:14.540 --> 00:18:20.960
Finally, Fonovisa brought
suit against the flea market.

00:18:20.960 --> 00:18:24.840
Because Cherry Auction was not
itself copying or distributing

00:18:24.840 --> 00:18:31.120
Fonovisa's works, Cherry was not liable
for direct copyright infringement.

00:18:31.120 --> 00:18:37.120
But if the facts were as Fonovisa
alleged, then some of the vendors

00:18:37.120 --> 00:18:40.560
were surely violating
Section 1063 and were not

00:18:40.560 --> 00:18:46.360
shielded by the first sale doctrine
embodied in section 109(a).

00:18:46.360 --> 00:18:49.970
If the reasons why the vendors were
engaged in copyright infringement

00:18:49.970 --> 00:18:52.200
are not clear to you,
you should pause here

00:18:52.200 --> 00:18:57.370
to review the first segment
of lecture number eight.

00:18:57.370 --> 00:19:02.650
Fonovisa contended that Cherry Auction
was secondarily liable for the vendors'

00:19:02.650 --> 00:19:07.100
unlawful behavior, both under the
doctrine of contributory infringement

00:19:07.100 --> 00:19:10.600
and under the doctrine of
vicarious infringement.

00:19:10.600 --> 00:19:13.460
The trial court was unpersuaded
and dismissed the suit for failure

00:19:13.460 --> 00:19:17.060
to state a claim upon which
relief could be granted.

00:19:17.060 --> 00:19:22.240
The Court of Appeals for the Ninth
Circuit reversed and remanded the case.

00:19:22.240 --> 00:19:26.440
In the opinion explaining its
decision, the Ninth Circuit clarified

00:19:26.440 --> 00:19:32.320
and arguably expanded both
secondary liability doctrines.

00:19:32.320 --> 00:19:34.660
With respect to
contributory infringement,

00:19:34.660 --> 00:19:38.910
the court ruled that Fonovisa had
sufficiently alleged knowledge

00:19:38.910 --> 00:19:42.060
of the infringing sales on
the part of Cherry Auction.

00:19:42.060 --> 00:19:44.850
More importantly and
controversially, the court

00:19:44.850 --> 00:19:48.200
ruled that quote material
contribution close

00:19:48.200 --> 00:19:52.510
